Canadian Law


In order to ensure appropriate enforcement of the law, we must know the law

In order to wield the full power of the law against those who break it, we must know the law intimately

In order to hold politicians and propaganda outlets accountable, we must understand the nature of relevant criminal code sections and the path to enforcement



-------> Section 122 of the Canadian criminal code:

Breach of public trust

- Criminal offences relating to public officers:
- Offences relating to breach of public trust are found in Part IV of the Criminal Code concerning "Offences Against the Administration of Law and Justice"

122 Every official who, in connection with the duties of their office, commits fraud or a breach of trust, whether or not the fraud or breach of trust would be an offence if it were committed in relation to a private person, is guilty of

    (a) an indictable offence and liable to imprisonment for a term of not more than five years; or

    (b) an offence punishable on summary conviction.



-------> Section 136 of the Canadian criminal code

Related to spreading false news

Makes it a criminal offense to wilfully publish false news or tales that cause or are likely to cause injury or mischief to a public interest

